<span id="freeTextContainer17054587475105269953">“<a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/208631.Ocean_Sea' title='Ocean Sea by Alessandro Baricco' rel='nofollow noopener'>Ocean Sea</a>” was recommended to me by fellow PhD student from university I was visiting. And I was very surprised when on the last day of my visit she gave me this book as a gift. This is one of the very few books gifted to me not by my family members and without me asking for it. Thank you, Michela!<br/><br/>Before starting this book, I didn’t have any expectations, only some examples from the plot. But I was asked to give the impression about it when I finish. So I started comparing it to something I hav</span>
  <span id="freeText17054587475105269953" style="display:none">“<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/208631.Ocean_Sea" title="Ocean Sea by Alessandro Baricco" rel="nofollow noopener">Ocean Sea</a>” was recommended to me by fellow PhD student from university I was visiting. And I was very surprised when on the last day of my visit she gave me this book as a gift. This is one of the very few books gifted to me not by my family members and without me asking for it. Thank you, Michela!<br /><br />Before starting this book, I didn’t have any expectations, only some examples from the plot. But I was asked to give the impression about it when I finish. So I started comparing it to something I have read before. First thing to come in my mind was the setting. An inn on the seashore. It reminded me of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/24197.Michael_Koryta" title="Michael Koryta" rel="nofollow noopener">Michael Koryta</a> “<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8585317.The_Cypress_House" title="The Cypress House by Michael Koryta" rel="nofollow noopener">The Cypress House</a>”. And this is the end of similarities of these two books, because the stories cannot be more different.<br /><br />Then I started to look for comparison of a writing style. But before that I would like to talk about style of the book in general. I was told that in Italian it is really beautiful, but this might not be translated equally well into English. But I loved how <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/15147790.Alastair_McEwan" title="Alastair McEwan" rel="nofollow noopener">Alastair McEwan</a> translated <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/908.Alessandro_Baricco" title="Alessandro Baricco" rel="nofollow noopener">Alessandro Baricco</a>. Actually, this is the first time when I felt that English language can be organic or flowy. I am not sure how to best describe it, but it is simply beautiful. It defies a lot of grammatical rules and, if written in “MS Word”, half of the sentences would be underlined in green - <i>Fragment (consider revising)</i>. But that’s that makes it so easy to read for me. Maybe it reminds me of Lithuanian language, which has more freedom in the order of the words in the sentence. In this book, a lot of sentences were written from the end to beginning compared to normal sentences. I used to think that English is very strict and doesn’t have much artistic freedom. But this book is complete opposite. Also, the words are very simple and the stories are very simple, but somehow it still doesn’t feel real. The simplicity of writing style and topics reminded me of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/3354.Haruki_Murakami" title="Haruki Murakami" rel="nofollow noopener">Haruki Murakami</a>. But there are subtle differences between these two authors. It took me awhile to find the correct words for it, but I think I managed it. Haruki Murakami writes more surreal things, while Alessandro Baricco – ethereal. Really, I cannot think of any other word to describe it. It’s like seeing something, trying to reach that thing, but not being able to. If you have no idea what I am talking about, just read the book – it is worth it.<br /><br />That I described earlier is mostly in the first part of the book and I liked it the most. Here the reader meets all the characters while they arrive at the Almayer Inn: <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[a painter, who paints sea with sea; a scientist, who tries to find the end of the sea; a woman, who seeks solitude from her husband and from her lover; a girl, who has a mysterious fear; a priest, who protects the girl and writes poems; a stranger, who doesn’t like to be noticed; a few children, who run the inn <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. In second part reader follows the event at sea told by two different people. This part is very different from the first one, it even shows some cruelty. At first it looks like it is not related to any of the previous stories. But everything becomes clear in the third part. Here every chapter is dedicated to different character and reader learns about their destiny. And every chapter brings different emotions: happiness, laughter, sadness, astonishment, interest and everything in between.<br /><br />I am really glad that this book was recommended to me. And I think it won’t be the last one I read from Alessandro Baricco.</span>
