  <span id="freeText18280631127237654761" style="display:none">I grabbed this book because it was published the year I was born. I did not read the synopsis, did not look around for reviews or ask my friends if they'd read it, I loved the title and it came out in 1993 so that was enough for me.<br /><br />That's why, when I started reading, I had absolutely no expectations and when those nasty things are out of the way, it is just so easy to become spellbound by the words flowing through your eyes, into your mind. After the first 20 pages I was absolutely certain that Ocean Sea was going to join the elite of my favorite books and it most definitely did.<br /><br />Baricco has his own, very experimental and ragged, effortlessly charming, way of writing that you just can't get enough of. Through his colorful and fresh use of language he presents you a puzzle, in this work, a puzzle of people and places and feelings, which is almost a riddle. He gives you bits and pieces without choking you with information, which I loved, because it gives the reader thinking space. You start wondering and trying to connect the dots just before Baricco himself shows you how things are, no, how things MIGHT be, and you find yourself admiring the imaginative wit of this author.<br /><br />I recommend this to anyone who is interested in the very best of contemporary Italian literature.</span>
